:::summary
The Moon is Earth's only natural satellite — a silent, cratered world that has governed tides, measured time, and inspired wonder since the earliest days of human history. Created by God on the fourth day as the "lesser light to rule the night" (Genesis 1:16), the Moon has been central to religious calendars, agricultural cycles, navigation, and poetry across every civilization. The Apollo missions of the 1960s and 1970s — among the greatest achievements in human history — placed human footprints on its surface and transformed our understanding of Earth's nearest celestial neighbor.
:::

